x4freetext: variable-energy 88" Lawrence Radiation
Laboratory cyclotron
Two cooled detector telescopes
were used to make measurements over an angular range
of 10. degr. to 170. degr. in the lab system. Each
telescope consisted of a 100 mu-m thick silicon
surface barrier dDE detector and a 5 mm thick silicon
lithium-drifted E-detector. The over-all energy
resolution of the detected protons was found to
be around 50 keV (FWHM).
2.77 mg/cm2 beryllium target
Reactor grade beryllium with 0.5% oxygen, 0.08% carbon
The error in the absolute normalization is
* due to uncertainties in the charge collection
efficiency, possible variations in the target thickness
* uncertainties in the solid angles subtended by the
detectors, and
* uncertainties in the correction terms.
Combination of these factors leads to an uncertainty
in the absolute normalization of ~ 2.4%.
